---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover">
  <h1>A long time ago...</h1>
</p-slide>

<p-slide arrow-time>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">The classic design system</h3>
  <div class="hand-drawing center mid-dimension">
    <span data-box>🎨 Sources — Sass / JS</span>
    <p-fragment>
      <span data-arrow data-down></span>
      <span data-box>⚙️ Build step — Sass, PostCSS, plugins</span>
    </p-fragment>
    <p-fragment>
      <span data-arrow data-down></span>
      <span data-box>🎟️ Generated CSS tokens</span>
    </p-fragment>
    <p-fragment>
      <span data-arrow data-down></span>
      <span data-box>📦 Shipped bundle</span>
    </p-fragment>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Walk the pipeline as it reveals — most people in this room live it every
      day.
    </p>
    <p>
      Land the key idea: tokens are a generated artifact, a Sass/JS source
      compiled down to CSS variables.
    </p>
    <p>
      Stay neutral here — don't bash the pipeline yet. The critique comes on the
      next slide.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">The hidden cost</h2>
  <ul style="">
    <li>
      🔁 <span>Every change = </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >a new build</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧱 <span
        >Dependencies to maintain and <span class="main-sub-gradient"
          >update</span
        ></span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🔒 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Lock-in to</span><span>
        tools and their conventions</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🧊 <span>Themes and variants </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >"frozen" at build time</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Turn the screws gently — each bullet is real friction, not a dealbreaker.
    </p>
    <p>
      Emphasize "frozen at build time": that's the thread the whole talk pulls
      on.
    </p>
    <p>
      Transition: we accept all of this... but how much of it is actually
      necessary today?
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="center" autoplay timing="550">
  <h2 class="main-gradient" style="margin-block-end: 0.5em">
    What if the browser could do most of this work?
  </h2>
  <p-fragment>
    <span style="font-size: 1.5em;">( ๑‾̀◡‾́)✨</span>
  </p-fragment>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Pause. Let the question sit before the emoji lands.</p>
    <p>This is the hinge of the talk — say it slowly.</p>
    <p>
      Be honest about the answer: "a lot, but not all" — which is exactly the
      next section.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1 style="font-size: 1.5em">Build-time vs Runtime</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>Short breath. Just announce the section.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide class="center">
  <h4 class="main-gradient" style="margin-block-end: 0.5em">
    It's not about throwing the tools away
  </h4>
  <p
    p-effect="from below"
    style="font-size: 0.8em; opacity: 0.8; margin-block-start: 1em"
  >
    It's a shift in mindset
  </p>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Pre-empt the defensive reaction — half the room ships with Vite/PostCSS
      and I'm not attacking them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frame it: the question isn't "tools or no tools", it's "what runs when".
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 class="main-gradient center">What belongs to the browser?</h2>
</p-slide>
<p-slide b-v-r>
  <div
    style="display: grid; text-align: center; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5em;"
  >
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <h4 style="margin-block: 0.3em 0.6em;">
        ⚙️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">Build-time</span>
      </h4>
      <p style="font-size: 0.5em; margin-block: 0 0.4em; opacity: 0.8;">
        still useful
      </p>
      <ul style="font-size: 0.7em;">
        <li>Bundling &amp; minification</li>
        <li>Asset optimization</li>
        <li>Type-checking</li>
        <li>Legacy browser fallbacks</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div p-effect="from right">
      <h4 style="margin-block: 0.3em 0.6em;">
        🌐 <span class="main-sub-gradient">Runtime</span>
      </h4>
      <p style="font-size: 0.5em; margin-block: 0 0.4em; opacity: 0.8;">
        the browser handles it today
      </p>
      <ul style="font-size: 0.7em;">
        <li>Theming &amp; dark mode</li>
        <li>Shade generation</li>
        <li>Fluid scales without breakpoints</li>
        <li>Scoping &amp; layering</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Left column first: these genuinely stay at build time — don't undersell
      them.
    </p>
    <p>
      Right column: these used to need a build, now the browser does them
      natively. That's the whole point.
    </p>
    <p>
      Anticipated question: someone will ask about browser support — say we'll
      be honest about it at the end (section 9).
    </p>
    <p>
      If short on time, skip reading every bullet — the contrast is the message.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2 class="main-gradient">From "frozen" to "live"</h2>
  <ul class="more-margin">
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Before: every shade and theme <span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >generated at build time</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      Today: CSS computes them <span class="main-sub-gradient">at runtime</span
      >, in the browser
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      <code>@layer</code>, <code>@scope</code>, <code>color-mix()</code>,
      <code>light-dark()</code>, <code>clamp()</code>…
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is the teaser — read the function names out loud, they're the table
      of contents for the rest of the talk.
    </p>
    <p>Don't explain them yet: "we'll see each of these in action".</p>
    <p>Transition into section 3 — governing the cascade.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<style lang="scss">
  ul.more-margin {
    font-size: 0.8em;
  }
  [arrow-time] {
    span {
      &[data-arrow] {
        font-size: 1em;
      }
    }
  }
  [b-v-r] {
    ul {
      margin-block-start: 1.3em;
      li {
        margin-block-end: 0.4em;
      }
    }
  }
</style>
